<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-02-16T09:35:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-02-16T09:35:00-05:00" n="578" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d578">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">791.003/71: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Persia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Philip</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Teheran</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-02-16T18:00:00+03:25"><hi rend="italic">February 16,
                                        1928—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received February 16—1:50
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>14. My 10, February 8, paragraph 3, subdivision (2).<note n="9" xml:id="d578fn9">Not printed.</note> I now find the Persian
                            Government’s attitude toward the “most-favored-nation” clause, as
                            expressed to the British and German Ministers by Teimourtache,<note n="10" xml:id="d578fn10">Abdul Hussein Teimourtache, Minister of the
                                Court in Persia.</note> is as follows: Persia will not object to use
                            of this phrase in the treaties with regard to all treaty privileges
                            except those which relate to tariff matters. Regarding these, Persia
                            will insist upon employing some other phrase, which may imply similar
                            rights.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Philip</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>